<br>
I would highly recommend upgrading to either XP or 2000 if you plan on purchasing SoL.  For some unknown reason, Verant increased the system requirements to see the new character models to 256 MBs of RAM minimum, yet they didn't mention the fact that Windows 98 can't allocate more than 128 MBs of RAM to any one application and its listed as one of the operating systems supported.  /shrug<br>
<br>
Windows ME....*shudder*  Let's not speak of such things here. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
So if you're going with SoL, look at upgrading soon.  Especially if you want to see the new character models.<br>
<br>
I run 2000 on my machine &amp; haven't had a problem yet.  Although I am having a few difficulties with DirectX 8.1 using the new *.dll, but that's expected since I like to poke &amp; prod with programs a lot.<br>
<br>
A few words on comparing 2000/XP to 95/98/ME:<br>
<br>
2000/XP are based off the Windows NT kernel, and as such are designed more for a networked enviroment.  (That's what the &quot;NT&quot; stands for, network)  While not overly more difficult to use than 95/98/ME, things are a bit different from what you might know now.<br>
<br>
The NT based systems are better at managing memory for applications, such that when you run a game you'll really be getting all the &quot;juice&quot; out of your system that you can.  Very simplistic way of putting it, but that's something that 95/98/ME don't do nearly as well<br>
<br>
Its difficult to list all the pros &amp; cons of these operating systems in one post without invoking lots of questions and long winded debate over what's the better system, but suffice it to say that if you have a higher end machine, you'll get the most out of it by using 2000/XP.  Also, Microsoft is effectively phasing out the 95 kernel, so silly things like drivers &amp; support for those older OS's probably won't be around forever.<br>
<br>
Amanhann<br>
